#System Design

The Security Operations Center (SOC) in this project is built within a controlled virtualized environment comprising multiple virtual 
machines (VMs): the Attacker (via Atomic Red Team and Metasploit), the Victim (Windows), and the SOC (Ubuntu Server with ELK Stack). 
The system is designed to simulate real-world cyberattacks and evaluate the effectiveness of the ELK Stack in detecting, visualizing, and 
responding to these attacks using the MITRE ATT&CK framework for correlation.

#System Architecture Overview

The system architecture consists of three core components, each serving a distinct role:

1. Attacker (via Atomic Red Team and Metasploit): Attack simulations are carried out using Atomic Red Team and Metasploit, both of which 
simulate various adversary tactics, techniques, and procedures (TTPs) aligned with the MITRE ATT&CK framework. These tools are executed 
either from the Kali Linux VM or the SOC environment.
2. Victim (Windows): Configured as the target machine, running Windows OS, which will be subjected to simulated attacks.
3. SOC (Ubuntu Server with ELK Stack): Hosts the ELK Stack (Elasticsearch, Logstash, Kibana), which is responsible for collecting, 
processing, and visualizing the logs generated during simulated attacks. This machine also correlates attack patterns with the MITRE 
ATT&CK framework.

These components are interconnected within a private network, ensuring controlled communication with static IP addresses assigned to each 
machine. This isolated environment allows for comprehensive testing without external network interference.

#Network Topology

The network topology follows a centralized configuration, where the SOC machine (Ubuntu Server with ELK Stack) serves as the central monitoring and data collection
point. The attack simulation tools (via Atomic Red Team and Metasploit) and the Windows 10 VM (victim) are interconnected within a private network, ensuring controlled 
communication and log forwarding without external network interference.
